<dl id="n56123a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56123a">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56123a"> 123(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> search / love / knowledge / competence / unity / stupefaction / altruism <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56123a"><li>FW 604.31ff </li><li><a href="../../flex/tb/lextb.htm#n56123a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/tb/l39tb.htm#n56123a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56123a">MS BL 47488.57v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:090 <a name="tad4" href="../../ff/fdra/tda.htm#tbd7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/tb/tbd7.htm#n56123a">Draft: IV&sect;2.7</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">So in the Mantak of al-Tayr (Colloquy of the Flyers) the Birds, emblems of souls, seeking the presence of the gigantic feathered biped Simurgh, their god, traverse seven Seas (according to other seven Wadys) of <mark>Search, of Love, of Knowledge, of Competence, of Unity, of Stupefaction, and of Altruism</mark> (<i>i.e.</i> annihilation of self), the several stages of contemplative life. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE4" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE4"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 130</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also: <a name="n38221d" href="n38all.htm#n38221d">N38 (VI.B.32):221(d)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
